ew York industry, however, the focus was on mass production. American buyers, trend scouts, and designers crossed the Atlantic to attend couture openings, where they were inspired by, and often accused of counterfeiting, designs made in Paris. For their part, Paris couturiers traveled to New York to understand what American consumers wanted and to make deals with local manufacturers for whom they designed exclusive garments and accessories. The cooperation and competition between the two continents transformed the fashion industry in the early and mid-twentieth century, producing a hybrid of art and commodity. Véronique Pouillard shows how the Paris–New York connection gave way in the 1960s to a network of widely distributed design and manufacturing centers. Since then, fashion has diversified. Tastes are no longer set by elites alone, but come from the street and from countercultures, and the business of fashion has transformed into a global enterprise.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aClothing tradezFrancezParisxHistoryy20th century. 0aClothing tradezNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aFashion designzFrancezParisxHistoryy20th century. 0aFashion designzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aGlobalization. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Textile Industry.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073911440uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674259485zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674259485423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674259485/original  a978-3-11-073911-4  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  